      text: 'Let me offer what I think is the key question for international relations theory in the current moment: whether the norms, institutions, and practices of the liberal international order represent genuinely universal values and interests, or whether they represent the particular interests of the states that designed them — primarily the United States and its Western allies — projected onto the international system in a way that serves the dominant powers while constraining the choices of others. If the former, then the challenge is to preserve and extend the order against revisionist challengers. If the latter, then what we are witnessing is not the defence of universal norms but a power struggle between established and rising powers, in which the rhetoric of "rules-based order" functions as an ideological device to delegitimise the choices of those who did not write the rules. Not only does this distinction matter for how we understand current conflicts — it matters enormously for how we think about what a legitimate post-American international order might look like.',
